node.text:
I watched a movie ‘12 Years a Slave’ which is about the time when black people were treated as slaves by birth in the United States. Not only in United States but in many parts where colour, family background, sex, caste defines our course of lives. That movie shook me to core, how humans of one particular color can decide to be superior and chose the path of cruelity to supress other colour to an extent that they start being inhumane! 
I feel colours of our soul is what makes us, not the shade of our skin.
,
,

Hues of our soul makes us who we are , 
there are zillion of shades beaneath our heart 
our blacks and whites are  on incessant war! 
our yellows and greens are hoping to get uncaged! 
our colours of our heart makes us magnificent, 
yet everyone cares for colour of our skin
blacks,white, negro, albino, hispanic are all treated different!
can we'all just stop discriminating on gendrer  colour, race, or caste 
and celebrate all shades of our heart!
.
.
.
My first Canvas painting symbolising that its the work of individuals defines their shades of personality from millions of colours and he himself is the reason for his heaven or hell on earth.

node.text:
•⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
"I am fine". " I am okay". "It's all cool". ⁣ These are few of the infamous lies used by the ones suffering inside. The saddest part is that most people fall for these lies and forget how deeply hurt someone could be to mask their true feelings. ⁣
⁣
Is it because they are afraid to trust someone? Are they too embarassed? Are they in fear of humiliation? Whatever the reason maybe, it forces us to reflect how deep a hole does our societal norms and pressure imposes on people. Nobody is weal, just afraid to be out in the open, afraid to be vulnerable because to them and a lot of us, we are just prey to the vultures dressed in human skin. ⁣
⁣
Although I believe in equality but through my own life experiences I believe the old saying - "A woman's heart is as deep as the ocean", and you'd be amazed at how much she can keep within until it floods out together. ⁣
⁣
I wish we all would understand just how damaged the world has become and take a step to change. It is easy to to submit and survive but it takes a hell lot of courage, conviction and willpower to feel alive even for a little while. That my friend is called Living. ⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣
— @theshrewdshrink • #theshrewdshrink⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣⁣

#DidYouKnow that Ganesh Chaturthi was once patronised by the erstwhile family of the Peshwa who had his seat of power in Pune. After the decline of the Peshwa after the arrival of the British, nationalist leader Bal Gangadhar Tilak revived the festival in the late 19th century. The photo video gives you a sneak peek into the celebrations of this vibrant festival. Sahapedia wishes everyone a Blessed and Eco Friendly Ganesh Chaturthi. 

If you enjoy the work we do, please consider making a donation to support the efforts towards the documentation and dissemination of India's rich cultural heritage. Donate now- link in bio.

node.text: ' Intellect does not easily break down, whereas love can effortlessly reduce itself to rubble. But treasures are hidden among ruins. A broken heart hides treasures. ‘
' Intellect does not easily break down, whereas love can effortlessly reduce itself to rubble. But treasures are hidden among ruins. A broken heart hides treasures. ‘

I took this selfie in a moment of peace at my house in Los Angeles. I look tired and hopeful because that’s what that moment felt to me. I was at the end of an incredibly exhausting year, and I was looking forward for the exhausting part to end, so that I could enjoy that new place, a place where I was learning to live by myself for the first time in my life. I was choosing my furniture, defining what I wanted my life to feel like, day in and day out. I identified with the pomegranate tree in this little garden, which was completely bare, so bare I had worried it could be dead (I don’t know anything about plants). But instead, one day, I saw the smallest green leaf sprouting out of those branches which had looked so lifeless. You cannot imagine what strength that sprout gave me. I didn’t know that I wouldn’t get to experience much of the quiet after the storm I was dreaming about, I didn’t know that shortly after this moment a pandemic would hit the world and I would have to leave this house in a matter of hours. I am lucky, I can work from anywhere and I always had a beautiful place to stay. Yet, I experienced tremendous loss because of the pandemic. I had to readjust my plans, my habits, deal with extra bureaucracy, with office closures and missing documents. With safety concerns and with the psychological turmoil that hit me and the people around me. I am a naturally resilient person, I always try to focus on the positive, so it took a while for me to even admit to myself what I was feeling, and to allow myself to feel it, without judgement. Through this entire time, I received help from the most unexpected people: strangers in some cases who helped me manage this difficult transition with small and big favors. If you can help someone in big or small ways, please do. We’re all going through a really tough time and we can all use all the help we can get to get through this, together.
